ul><h2 id=3D"faqs-on-set-theory" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Commonly A=
sked Questions on Set Theory</span></h2><h3 id=3D"what-is-the-basis-of-set-=
theory" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>What is the basis of set theory?</s=
pan></h3><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Set Theory is the study of a coll=
ection of objects which are called sets and the relation between different =
sets.</span></p></blockquote><h3 id=3D"how-do-you-define-set" style=3D"text=
-align:left"><span>How do you define a set?</span></h3><blockquote><p dir=
=3D"ltr"><span>Set is a well-defined collection of objects. These objects a=
re called the element of sets.</span></p></blockquote><h3 id=3D"who-invente=
d-set-theory" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Who Invented Set Theory?</spa=
n></h3><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Set Theory was invented by German M=
athematician Georg Cantor.</span></p></blockquote><h3 id=3D"what-is-the-alg=
ebra-of-sets" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>What is the Algebra of Sets?<=
/span></h3><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Algebra of Sets deals with the =
following laws:</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>Commutative Laws</span>=
</li><li value=3D"2"><span>Associative Law</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span=
>Distributive Law</span></li><li value=3D"4"><span>Identity Law</span></li>=
<li value=3D"5"><span>Idempotent Law</span></li></ul><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>T=
hese laws are covered in the article under Properties of Sets.</span></p></=
blockquote><h3 id=3D"what-is-a-subset" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>What=
 is a Subset?</span></h3><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>A subset is a set=
 that has fewer or equal elements of another set. The other set is called a=
 Superset.</span></p></blockquote><h3 id=3D"what-is-de-morgans-law" style=
=3D"text-align:left"><span>What is De Morgan's Law?</span></h3><blockquote>=
<p dir=3D"ltr"><span>De Morgan's Law is a law that deals with the union and=
 intersection of sets with the intersection and union of individual sets re=
spectively. There are two laws under it namely De Morgan's Law of Union and=
 De Morgan's Law of Intersection. These are covered under the section of De=
 Morgan's Law in this article.</span></p></blockquote>                     =
